Title: Homeland Defense Over the Horizon Radar Development                                                                           367.454       0.000        77.948
Description: HLD OTHR development focuses on radar system design, development, manufacture and acquisition of hardware
and software for the Transmit (TX) and Receive (RX) sites. Efforts include continuing modeling and simulation tools, mission
studies, as well as analyses to inform systems engineering, early test activities, and warfighter concepts of employment
(CONEMP). Modeling will validate performance characteristics and metrics unique to NORAD/USNORTHCOM (N/NC) mission.
In addition, federally funded research and development centers and service labs are developing a system-of-systems design to
inform a Government Reference Architecture (GRA) for use as an authoritative source of truth. Future acquisition strategies will
require acquiring a system-of-systems aligned to, and/or built upon, the GRA.

FY 2026 Plans:
The following CY efforts are being executed using FY 2025 carryover funds and are also be communicated in the BA7 R-Doc:
- Conducting wintertime experimentation study (install, checkout, operate) with DoD S&T community
- Utilizing Winter Study results and ionospheric model development to inform predicted performance metrics
- Continue ionospheric model development, and start tool improvements to improve system performance at northern latitudes
- Start system design via GRA development while evaluating/researching supply chain market to meet intended system design
- Complete planned integration activities in support of classified requirements
FY 2027 Plans:
- Utilize Winter Study results and ionospheric model to inform system design and algorithm development
- Continue system design and supply chain market research
- Develop training material and technical documentation for operators
- Complete set of planned activities are held at a higher level
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2026 President's Budget submittal did not reflect the FY 2027 through FY 2030 funding. Therefore, an explanation of the
changes between the two budget positions for FY 2027 cannot be made in a relevant manner.
