A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Efforts funded in this program focus on development, testing, and fielding, of a long-range early detection capability for airborne and surface targets of interest. Each
line of effort acquires and fields a land based, high-frequency (HF) ionospheric, backscatter Over-the-Horizon RADAR (OTHR) for detection and tracking of airborne and
surface targets over wide geographic areas. Fielding of this capability will enable detection, tracking and reporting of airborne and surface targets that may be obscured
from conventional line of sight radar systems by the curvature of the earth.

 Tactical Multi-Mission Over the Horizon Radar(TACMOR) is a US Air Force remotely operated OTHR system being developed for deployment in the Republic of Palau
 (RoP). The system will provide enhanced Air Domain Awareness in key regions of USINDOPACOM's area of responsibility.

 This program may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would
 be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program element 0605827F, 0605828F, 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605832F, 0605833F, 0605898F, 0606398F. In
 FY 2025 0.000 million was expended for civilian pay expenses in this program, in FY 2026 0.111 million is forecasted for civilian pay expenses in this program element.

 TACMOR FY 2026 funds were allocated to - Program 012417F Project 674865 (budget authority 7). FY 2027-FY 2031 corrects the budget authority from 7 to 5 to
 appropriately reflect program efforts.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025           FY 2026        FY 2027
Title: TACMOR Development                                                                                                                    9.543             0.000         96.027
Description: TACMOR development focuses on rapid prototyping activities to field an OTHR system capable of operating under
challenging ionospheric conditions near the equator in the Republic of Palau.
Key activities include: Prototype design, development, production, installation, and testing activities; Conducting engineering
studies and analyses to inform system design; Research and scientific studies to characterize ionospheric and electromagnetic
interference phenomenology to inform the design and development of transmit, receive, and software subsystems; Development
of ionospheric models to support sensor tracking software; Development, integration, and testing of sensor suite command-
and-control (C2) software; Implementation of Model-Based Digital Engineering tools and principles; Development of system
modeling and simulation tools and environments; Design and development of unique system security, cybersecurity, resiliency,
and hardening features to meet TACMOR's high-threat environment requirements; Design and implementation of communication
and control (C2) and data fusion architectures; Design and installation of a high-speed Fiber-Optic communications system.



