                                                                                 ation$$, $$$$, $$The acquisition strategy is uniquely structured to be flexible and data-driven, with the final procurement pathway contingent on the results of advanced prototyping efforts
conducted by the Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL). The data and insights gained from AFRL's work are pivotal and will inform a key strategic decision between
two primary acquisition approaches:
1. DoW-Led Tail Kit Assembly (TKA) Acquisition: If the data supports a standard development effort, the program will follow a model like the successful B61 LEP
program. A dedicated USAF System Program Office (SPO) will manage the competitive procurement of the weapon's Tail Kit Assembly (TKA), while the Department of
Energy/National Nuclear Security Administration (DOE/NNSA) provides the nuclear bomb assembly.
2. DOE/NNSA-Led Full System Procurement: Alternatively, if the AFRL prototyping demonstrates a sufficiently mature and low-risk design, the data may justify an
alternative pathway where the DOE/NNSA procures the entire weapon system (the "all-up round").

In either scenario, the USAF SPO's responsibility will be to oversee as the platform integration with the weapon and procurement of transportation & handling gear,
trainers, and ancillary equipment. The SPO will oversee the complex and critical task of integrating the complete Next Generation Gravity Bomb with its threshold
aircraft, ultimately ensuring the platform achieves full nuclear certification.

The SPO will analyze the AFRL prototype data once available to formally recommend the most prudent acquisition path.

