Remarks

D. Acquisition Strategy
The new variant of the B61 Tail Kit Assembly (TKA) program is a strategic initiative to address a critical U.S. nuclear deterrent capability, as directed by the 2022
Nuclear Posture Review. In November 2025 President Donald J. Trump published the National Security Strategy (NSS) directing the development of a "modern nuclear
deterrent… to protect the American people, American assets overseas, and American allies”. In addition, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth published the 2026 National
Defense Strategy (NDS) directing action to develop modern nuclear deterrent assets capable of addressing strategic threats to our country. Furthermore, Secretary
Hegseth directed the modernization and adaptation of our nuclear forces with "focused attention on deterrence and escalation management”. The program's core
objective is to rapidly and cost-effectively deliver a modernized gravity bomb by leveraging proven technology.

The acquisition strategy utilizes a low-risk, expedited Mid-Tier Acquisition (MTA) pathway. It avoids new technology development by modifying the existing, highly
reliable B61-12 TKA for use with the new B61 variant nuclear Bomb Assembly. This approach significantly reduces technical, programmatic, and cost risks. Boeing, the
original equipment manufacturer, will perform the necessary modifications.

Transitioning from administrative to engineered controlled -13 TKA delivers a software update, eliminating manual processes and mitigating long-term operational risk.




