Note
The Dept Air Force Electromagnetic Battle Management (DAF-EMBM) Program is aiming for end of CY27 to reach Early Operational Capability status for the system.
The program will do this over the next two years by developing minimum operational standards and metrics for success, experimenting with multiple exiting Government
off the Shelf systems to find best of breed for the required system capability, and then integrating them into a single functional system-of-systems suite to satisfy the
required standards.

DAF-EMBM system integration will tie multiple disparate systems together into a unified control and display unit integrating Non-Kinetic Effects (NKE) with
Electromagnetic Spectrum Operations (EMSO) into all other military operations, combining capabilities to manage, protect, exploit, and attack through the
electromagnetic spectrum (EMS). DAF-EMBM will consist of five components with the ability to attain and maintain: EMS Situational Awareness, EMS operational
planning, EMS decision support analytics, Command and Control, and user training. Efforts will revolve around the development of advanced software, and robust
meshed comm networking and data links.

The Weapons Control Test demonstrations (to include modeling and sim efforts) will enable the program to set the standards and metrics for measuring execution for the
system as it receives, analyzes, displays, employs, and securely distributes adversary and friendly EMS information.

PEO BIG IRON will act as the Integration Program Office until EOC is achieved and the prototype system is delivered. It will then hand off the further program efforts to
a robust EW System Program Office for the lifecycle execution of this and other parallel EW programs. An EW SPO does not currently exist so the EMBM Program will
build one from the ground up starting in FY26.




