A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The F-16 is a multi-role fighter that comprises roughly 40% of the USAF fighter fleet with 810 aircraft supporting a variety of air-to-air and air-to-surface missions,
such as offensive and defensive counter-air, close air support, forward air control, air interdiction (day/night and all-weather), and Suppression of Enemy Air Defenses
(SEAD)/Destruction of Enemy Air Defenses (DEAD). F-16 posture and readiness combined with low operating costs delivers affordable capacity for the USAF and
partner nations. Its capabilities continue to evolve, capitalizing upon advancements made in computers, avionics systems, engines, and structural technologies. These
advancements meet emerging warfighter requirements to combat current and evolving enemy threats. Funding described in this document provides upgrades to
the F-16 platform necessary for the delivery of joint lethality in the coming decades. These computer processing and avionics upgrades are critical to a modernized
architecture compatible with current open, agile, and digital concepts that will maintain platform viability into the 2040s.

Post-Block (40/42/50/52) and Pre-Block (30) F-16s have similar capabilities and are interoperable but require some independent modernization and sustainment of
hardware, software, and training.

The F-16 Foreign Military Sales (FMS) Program is one of the largest in DoW, providing assurance to 29 partners and growing. F-16 remains in production in South
Carolina and additional nations continue to commit to new aircraft purchases.

RDT&E efforts include, but are not limited to, enduring programs for Operational Flight Program (OFP) Software (SW) development, Integrated Test activities, Active
Electronically Scanned Array (AESA) radar, Simulators/Trainers, Integrated Viper Electronic Warfare Suite (IVEWS), Next Gen Mission Computer (NGMC)- New Start,
Engineering Manufacturing and Design (EMD) Hardware/Advanced capability improvements, M-Code, and Diminishing Manufacturing Sources (DMS). Programs
complete or nearing full development completion for Advanced Identification Friend or Foe (AIFF-Mode 5) APX-127, Data Bus Cybersecurity, and F-16 Electrical Test
Equipment.

The FY2026 spend plan amount for RDT&E includes $229,857 thousand of discretionary and $82,500 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $312,357
thousand. Mandatory funds are for the IVEWS program.



